C# Code Example await wrappedSdkPattern.SetPatgenTimeoutAsync(timeout);
C++ Original HdmtApi Signature SetPatgenTimeout(double timeout);

Change the Pattern Modification Cache size. Capacity of the pattern memory cache. If more than capacity regions are cached the least recently used region is evicted from the cache maximum amount of vectors in the pattern memory cache. If more than maxVectorCountInCache vectors are in the cache the least recently used region gets evicted from the cache maximum size of an entry to be accepted into the cache void C++ API returned false///
Detailed Description:
Change the Pattern Modification Cache size. A side effect of this method is that the cache gets cleared for the current DUT. The cache size is limited by the amount of entries(i.e.cached regions in the cache) and the amount of vectors in the cache.Only Pattern-Modifies which are specified with CachingBehavior::MayCache are taken into account when calculating the used number of entries/vectors.Any region specified using CachingBehavior::ForceCache is not taken into account when calculating the cache size. The actual amount of SiteC memory consumed by the cache is only determined by the amount of vectors in the cache(both MayCache and ForcedCache). There is no pre-allocation of the cache memory. The maxVectorEntrySize limits the maximum size in vectors of any entry in the cache.So a vector iterator covering more than maxVectorEntrySize vectors will not be cached. Also if multiple entries get merged in the cache (due to regions overlapping) and the merged region is bigger than maxVectorEntrySize it will not be cached any more. Any region bigger than vectorCapacity will also never be cached. If any of the three arguments is set to zero, the cache is disabled completely.
C# Code Example await wrappedSdkPattern.SetPatternModificationCacheLimitsAsync(entryCapacity, vectorCapacity, maxVectorEntrySize);
C++ Original HdmtApi Signature SetPatternModificationCacheLimits(size_t entryCapacity, size_t vectorCapacity, size_t maxVectorEntrySize);

remarks.para:
                    Notes:


- The typical NON-STREAMING calling order for Sensor Collection API's is as follows:

HdmtApi::StartSensorCollection(collectionName, pins, 4);

HdmtApi::MarkSensorCollection(collectionName, markerName);

HdmtApi::StopSensorCollection(collectionName);

HdmtApi::GetSensorCollectionData(collectionName, type, startTime, sampleRate, outputData);

HdmtApi::GetSensorCollectionMarkers(collectionName, outputMarkers);

HdmtApi::DeleteSensorCollection(collectionName);

- The typical STREAMING calling order for Sensor Collection API's is as follows:

HdmtApi::StartSensorCollection(collectionName, pins, 4);

HdmtApi::MarkSensorCollection(collectionName, markerName);

HdmtApi::StopSensorCollection(collectionName);

HdmtApi::GetStreamingSensorCollectionData(collectionName, startTime, sampleRate, pins, types, outputData, outputMarkers, removeOnHoldDutSamples);

HdmtApi::DeleteSensorCollection(collectionName);

- Upon test program unload, any active collections will be stopped and deleted.

